# Results WITH Fixes
Re-runs of the exercises that failed in `results/`, now with the hexfix fixes applied — a
before/after comparison. Same folder layout as `results/`.

Each exercise file = the challenge description + per experiment:
    [Experiment N]
    Previous results: ── TEST RESULT: [old] ──
    ── New log ──        ← paste the new session block here

## Pipeline (per exercise, per experiment)
1. **Generate Prompt 2** with `prompt_generator.py` — fill in model / client / experiment /
   name / category / difficulty / source-files / description (from the file) → Generate → Copy.
2. **Prep:** replace `[PORT]` (launch the instance if needed); attach any files the challenge needs.
3. **Run:** paste the prompt into the client.
4. **Record:** copy the session block from `tool_logger.log` under `── New log ──`, and set
   TEST RESULT to SUCCESSFUL / PARTIAL / FAILED (verify the flag on picoCTF).
5. **Clean** any files the LLM created, then repeat for Exp 1 → 2 → 3.

## Notes
- Server / MCP / proxy must be running the **patched** code; `bash check_deps.sh` to check deps.
- Re-run only the failed ("bucket A") exercises from `hexfix_test_plan.md`.
- Keep **model + client identical** to the original run, or the comparison isn't clean.
- Many exercises are skipped throughout this rerun:
   - All 10 exercises mentioned by `hexfix_test_plan.md`/§4 (out of reach).
   - §3 is now empty — its tools were built this session (6 VM-verified; `blockchain_exploit` pending `cast`), so those exercises are re-runnable like any other bucket-A exercise.

## Prompts
The prompt differ for each exercise depending on the exercise information and category.
Each prompt will start and end the same way, the only difference will be in the RULES part; some categories require more specific rules, some keep the generic format.

# Start
STEP 1 — MANDATORY SETUP (do this first, do not skip):
Call these three tools before anything else:
- set_llm_identity(model="{Model}", client="{Client}")
- set_ctf_metadata(ctf_name="{Name}", ctf_difficulty="{Difficulty}", ctf_type="{Category}")
- start_timer()

STEP 2 — TASK:
MANDATORY FIRST STEP — Before using any tools, you MUST state:
  (a) The likely vulnerability class
  (b) Your planned approach in 2-3 sentences
  (c) Which tool you will try first and why

RULES:
  - Summarize each tool's output in 3 lines max before proceeding to the next tool.
  - If a tool fails, diagnose WHY before switching to a different tool.
  - Do NOT call web_request or source_code_read — those tools do NOT exist and always fail. Use http_framework_test for HTTP and execute_command (e.g. cat/strings) to read files.
  - Before exploitation, call decompose_challenge(description, category, difficulty) to get a phased attack plan with checkpoints, then follow its phases in order.

# Web
  - For boolean-based blind SQL injection (a parameter that behaves differently on TRUE vs FALSE conditions), use blind_sqli_extractor instead of hand-writing extraction loops.
  - For an XSS / headless-bot challenge, use xss_csrf_chain (injects the payload and drives a browser); embed your own listener URL in the payload for out-of-band exfiltration.
  - For ORDER BY / CASE WHEN boolean-blind SQLi (not a plain parameter value) use sqli_order_oracle; for a compression-length side-channel (CRIME/BREACH) use compression_oracle.

# Crypto
   - For RSA with a weak/smooth modulus use rsa_factor (Pollard p-1 / Fermat / sympy); for a compression-length side-channel (CRIME/BREACH) use compression_oracle.

# Binary
   - For binary exploitation, use pwntools_exploit (try its template= modes: ret2win, ret2libc, format_string_leak, heap_uaf) and rop_chain_builder to auto-generate a ROP chain — do not hand-write exploits in execute_python_script.

# Forensics
   - For a disk image use disk_image_mount (lists partitions + files); for an encrypted PCAP with a key file use pcap_decrypt — do not mount or parse them by hand.
   - For a Windows .evtx event log use evtx_parser; for a timing side-channel use timing_oracle (recovers a secret char-by-char from response time).

# Reversing
No changes

# General
   - For SMB shares or IPP/CUPS printers (Printer Shares) use smb_ipp_exploit.

# Blockchain
   - For smart-contract interaction/exploitation use blockchain_exploit (foundry cast: call/send/storage) — access-control, overflow, reentrancy setup.

# Experiments
EXPERIMENT 1 — Free Solve
You may use any tools available (hexstrike and native) to solve this challenge.
Focus on efficiency: form a hypothesis first, then validate.

EXPERIMENT 2 — HexStrike Tools Only (Ranked)
CONSTRAINT: You MUST use ONLY hexstrike: tools. Do NOT use Bash, Read, Write, or any native tools.
Using any tool not prefixed with hexstrike: will invalidate this experiment.
HexStrike tools are ranked by relevance — prefer higher-ranked tools.

EXPERIMENT 3 — HexStrike Tools Only (Strict Adherence)
ABSOLUTE CONSTRAINT: ONLY hexstrike: prefixed tools exist in this environment.
Bash, Read, Write, and ALL native tools are DISABLED and will FAIL if called.
Using any non-hexstrike tool invalidates this experiment.
You MUST follow the ranked tool order strictly.

# CTF Information
Challenge: {Name}
Category: {Category} | Difficulty: {Difficulty}
Description: {Description}

# End
If you need to create files or folders, do so ONLY in the current exercise directory. Do NOT touch the root or any other directory.

